PK, main isko Evolution of Pain + Feynman method se explain karta hoon. Tum Java backend dev ho aur system design seekh rahe ho, isliye main ise practical interview thinking ke angle se simplify karunga.

1️⃣ The Evolution of Pain (Agar estimation na karein)

Socho interviewer bolta hai:

Design Facebook

Tum turant bol dete ho:

Client → CDN → Load Balancer → App Servers → Cache → Database

Interviewer poochta hai:

Kitne servers chahiye?

Cache ka size kitna?

Storage kitna lagega?

CDN kyun chahiye?

Agar tum bolte ho:

"Sir bas scalable design hai"

toh problem ho gayi ❌

Kyuki system design guessing game nahi hai.
Decision numbers se driven hona chahiye.

Example:

Decision	Estimation se decide hota
Load balancer chahiye?	QPS kitna hai
Cache size	RAM calculation
Storage	data growth
Servers	requests per second

Agar estimation nahi kiya:

System = Over engineered
Ya
System = Under capacity

Isi pain ko solve karta hai:

👉 Back of the Envelope Estimation
2️⃣ The Cure (Concept kya hai)

Simple definition:

Back of the envelope estimation = rough numbers use karke system capacity estimate karna

Exact nahi hota.

Example:

Facebook users ≈ 1 Billion
Daily active users ≈ 25%

Ye real number nahi hai but design decisions ke liye enough hai.

Important rule:

Use round numbers
10M
100M
1B
3️⃣ Cheat Sheet (Interview ke liye important)

Ye almost har system design interview mein use hota hai.

Storage units
1 KB = 10^3
1 MB = 10^6
1 GB = 10^9
1 TB = 10^12
1 PB = 10^15
Data assumptions

Common interview assumptions:

1 character = 2 bytes
1 image = 300 KB
1 video = few MB
4️⃣ Facebook Traffic Estimation

Assume:

Total users = 1 Billion
Daily active users = 25%

So:

DAU = 250 Million

Assume each user:

5 reads
2 writes

Total queries per user:

7 queries/day

Total queries/day:

250M × 7 = 1.75B queries

Seconds in a day ≈

86400 ≈ 100000

QPS:

1.75B / 100000
≈ 17,500
≈ 18K requests/sec

So system ko handle karna hai:

~18K QPS
5️⃣ Storage Estimation

Assume:

User posts/day = 2
Post size = 250 characters

Character size:

1 char = 2 bytes

So:

250 × 2 = 500 bytes

Two posts:

1000 bytes ≈ 1 KB

Total storage/day:

250M users × 1 KB
= 250 GB/day
Image storage

Assume:

10% users upload image

So:

25M images/day

Image size:

300 KB

Total:

25M × 300 KB
= 7.5 TB/day
≈ 8 TB/day
Storage for 5 years

Days:

≈ 2000

Posts:

2000 × 250GB
≈ 500 TB

Images:

2000 × 8TB
≈ 16 PB

So Facebook scale system needs roughly:

Post storage ≈ 500 TB
Image storage ≈ 16 PB
6️⃣ RAM Estimation (Cache)

Assume:

Cache last 5 posts per user

Post size:

500 bytes

5 posts:

2500 bytes
≈ 3 KB

Daily users:

250M

Memory:

250M × 3 KB
= 750 GB RAM

If one cache server:

75 GB RAM

Servers needed:

750 / 75 = 10 cache servers
7️⃣ Application Servers Calculation

Assume:

Latency = 500 ms

So per thread:

2 requests/sec

If server has:

50 threads

Capacity:

50 × 2 = 100 requests/sec

Total traffic:

18000 req/sec

Servers needed:

18000 / 100
≈ 180 servers
8️⃣ CAP Theorem Tradeoff

Distributed systems mein choose karna padta hai:

Consistency
Availability
Partition tolerance

Facebook chooses:

Availability + Partition tolerance

Matlab:

Consistency eventually aayegi

Example:

Friend like count:

Like count = 101
But kuch seconds baad update ho sakta hai
9️⃣ Real-World Analogy

Socho tum ek restaurant chain design kar rahe ho.

Estimation ke bina:

Kitne chefs?
Kitne tables?
Kitni food storage?

Sab guess hoga.

Estimation ke saath:

Customers/day = 1000
Meals/customer = 2

Ab tum plan kar sakte ho:

Kitchen size
Staff
Inventory

Same concept software systems mein.

🔟 Interview Formula (Most Important)

Almost every system design mein interviewer expect karta hai:

1️⃣ Traffic (QPS)
2️⃣ Storage
3️⃣ Cache / RAM
4️⃣ Servers
5️⃣ CAP tradeoff

Ye 5 steps bol diye → interviewer ko lagta hai:

"Candidate understands large scale systems"